WEBVTT

00:02.322 --> 00:13.453
♪♪

00:13.453 --> 00:25.906
♪♪

00:32.513 --> 00:35.556
[ Birds chirping ]

00:37.037 --> 00:39.319
[ Footsteps ]

00:40.721 --> 00:42.442
‐Devon, have you packed
your jacket?

00:42.442 --> 00:43.964
‐Yeah.

00:43.964 --> 00:46.486
‐And the tie?
‐Yeah, Mom, all the fancy shit.

00:46.486 --> 00:48.248
‐The green dress.
‐Good.

00:48.248 --> 00:49.530
That one looks nice on you.

00:49.530 --> 00:51.411
‐Can't ‐‐
Can't we just stay at Dad's?

00:51.411 --> 00:54.254
‐We have three more days.
We're spending it together.

00:54.254 --> 00:56.256
‐Mandy'll keep you company.
You don't need the both of us.

00:56.256 --> 00:58.779
‐No discussion.
To the car.

00:58.779 --> 01:00.701
‐[ Sighs ]

01:02.743 --> 01:06.066
‐His girlfriend's having a pool
party, and he wanted to go.

01:06.066 --> 01:09.349
‐He has a girlfriend?

01:09.349 --> 01:10.591
‐I liked that one.

01:10.591 --> 01:12.472
‐Me, too.

01:12.472 --> 01:14.555
‐We're willing to offer
a sizable settlement

01:14.555 --> 01:16.757
in return for your client
dropping all suits,

01:16.757 --> 01:18.278
as well as promising
not to engage

01:18.278 --> 01:20.761
any further with the press.

01:20.761 --> 01:22.963
Here is the figure we propose.

01:36.817 --> 01:39.660
[ Up‐tempo music plays ]
[ Indistinct conversations ]

01:39.660 --> 01:45.866
♪♪

01:45.866 --> 01:47.107
[ Music ends ]

01:47.107 --> 01:48.468
‐Whoo!
[ Cheers and applause ]

01:48.468 --> 01:51.752
‐Thank you, folks.
We'll be back in 15.

01:51.752 --> 01:53.233
‐Hey.
How were the chops?

01:53.233 --> 01:54.675
‐Perfect.
That was a good call.

01:54.675 --> 01:56.837
‐She's great.
‐They are something special.

01:56.837 --> 01:58.999
You guys staying
for the next set?

01:58.999 --> 02:00.801
‐Uh, you know what?
It's a school night.

02:00.801 --> 02:02.963
‐I think we're gonna roll.
‐Are you finished with that?

02:02.963 --> 02:05.045
‐Yeah. Yeah, thank you.
‐Okay. See you at home.

02:05.045 --> 02:07.247
‐Hey, what's the damage?
‐No. I got it.

02:07.247 --> 02:08.849
‐Oh, no, no. Let me.
‐Oh, it's fine.

02:08.849 --> 02:10.531
We get a discount.

02:10.531 --> 02:13.534
[ Indistinct conversations ]

02:13.534 --> 02:15.255
‐It seems like she's doing
really well.

02:15.255 --> 02:17.538
‐Yeah, getting by right now.

02:21.902 --> 02:24.064
What time do you
lose your sitter?

02:24.064 --> 02:26.827
‐Midnight.
‐Can I take you somewhere?

02:26.827 --> 02:27.828
[ Buffer whirring ]

02:27.828 --> 02:28.989
Hey.

02:28.989 --> 02:30.350
[ Clicks, whirring stops ]

02:30.350 --> 02:31.912
‐How you doing, Tom?
‐How are you?

02:31.912 --> 02:33.514
Hi.

02:33.514 --> 02:37.437
♪♪

02:37.437 --> 02:40.921
Thanks, Chicken.
‐Yeah, you got it, bud.

02:40.921 --> 02:43.363
‐His name is Chicken?

02:43.363 --> 02:45.085
[ Chuckles ]

02:58.659 --> 03:01.261
‐Did I make a mistake
by bringing you here?

03:03.704 --> 03:05.946
‐No.

03:05.946 --> 03:08.308
I'm glad you did.

03:08.308 --> 03:10.430
I like remembering him
like this.

03:10.430 --> 03:21.882
♪♪

03:21.882 --> 03:28.368
♪♪

03:28.368 --> 03:30.130
‐[ Spits ]

03:30.130 --> 03:31.772
All right. I won.

03:31.772 --> 03:33.814
‐Hey, uh, rematch!

03:33.814 --> 03:35.936
‐How many times
do you want to lose?

03:35.936 --> 03:38.098
♪♪

03:38.098 --> 03:40.621
‐He was so competitive.

03:40.621 --> 03:43.664
‐He used to get so angry
if I beat him at darts.

03:43.664 --> 03:46.026
‐Yeah, you cost us
a lot of quality time.

03:46.026 --> 03:49.069
[ Both laugh ]

03:49.069 --> 03:51.912
‐Denise went to swim camp here.

03:51.912 --> 03:55.075
First day down there
in the shallow end,

03:55.075 --> 03:57.758
she dives headfirst,

03:57.758 --> 03:59.439
bang, straight on her head.
‐Oh, no.

03:59.439 --> 04:01.001
‐It's bleeding like hell.

04:01.001 --> 04:02.683
‐She's not crying,
but when I tell her

04:02.683 --> 04:04.725
she's not gonna be able
to continue camp,

04:04.725 --> 04:07.928
it's like the horror‐film
version of a teenager saying,

04:07.928 --> 04:09.770
"Oh, my God, Dad!"

04:09.770 --> 04:12.092
[ Chuckles ] Like, you know?
‐[ Laughs ]

04:12.092 --> 04:13.774
Hey.

04:13.774 --> 04:17.137
Did Diane do this?

04:17.137 --> 04:19.580
‐It's how we first met.

04:19.580 --> 04:22.743
‐This one?
‐One and only.

04:22.743 --> 04:25.986
‐She was really talented.

04:25.986 --> 04:28.028
‐Yeah, she was.

04:30.991 --> 04:32.392
Should we roll?

04:32.392 --> 04:35.636
‐Yeah.
‐Let's do it.

04:35.636 --> 04:38.879
‐Earth, not space, that's how we
save the human race!

04:38.959 --> 04:42.763
Earth, not space, that's how
we save the human race!

04:42.843 --> 04:46.807
Earth, not space, that's how
we save the human race.

04:46.807 --> 04:48.328
‐Earth, not space ‐‐

04:48.328 --> 04:51.011
‐This is a fragment
from the upper level

04:51.011 --> 04:52.933
of the first stage.

04:52.933 --> 04:55.335
This portion here did not match

04:55.335 --> 04:57.297
any of the alloys
we used in the build.

04:57.297 --> 05:00.781
The composition was a mixture
of copper and nickel.

05:00.781 --> 05:02.863
It's a tradition
for the Providence crew

05:02.863 --> 05:04.705
to bring a quarter
into the White Room

05:04.705 --> 05:06.627
as a good luck ritual.

05:06.627 --> 05:08.669
The quarter was given
to a technician

05:08.669 --> 05:10.390
before they entered the capsule.

05:10.390 --> 05:12.432
We believe he must have
dropped it on to the transom,

05:12.432 --> 05:15.035
or it fell out of his pocket.

05:15.035 --> 05:19.119
The quarter was then lodged onto
a ‐‐ a spring‐loaded dust cover

05:19.119 --> 05:22.002
of one of the forward
booster separation motors

05:22.002 --> 05:24.404
on the starboard SRB right here.

05:26.847 --> 05:29.249
When the BSMs ignite,
these dust covers,

05:29.249 --> 05:32.052
they fling open due to
the 20,000 pounds of thrust

05:32.052 --> 05:34.054
generated by the BSM.

05:34.054 --> 05:36.537
When this happened, the quarter
was flung with enough velocity

05:36.537 --> 05:39.019
to puncture the LOX tank
of the first stage.

05:39.019 --> 05:40.981
The impact provided
an ignition source,

05:40.981 --> 05:43.624
enabling the aluminum skin
of the LOX tank

05:43.624 --> 05:46.707
to be rapidly consumed by fire,

05:46.707 --> 05:49.750
exacerbated by the presence
of pure oxygen in th‐‐

05:49.750 --> 05:51.471
‐Madam Chairperson, if I may.

05:51.471 --> 05:53.914
‐The Chair recognizes
the Senator from Massachusetts.

05:53.914 --> 05:56.717
‐These five lives were lost
because of a coin?

06:01.241 --> 06:02.723
‐We design these vehicles

06:02.723 --> 06:04.685
to meet
the anticipated environment

06:04.685 --> 06:08.168
in which
they're supposed to function.

06:08.168 --> 06:12.212
We consider thousands
of possible scenarios.

06:12.212 --> 06:14.054
What we didn't anticipate
was the equivalent

06:14.054 --> 06:15.976
of a high‐powered rifle
being shot point‐‐

06:15.976 --> 06:18.579
‐Five lives.

06:18.579 --> 06:21.381
That's what I'm trying
to wrap my head around.

06:21.381 --> 06:24.585
How do we justify the loss
of these lives?

06:27.307 --> 06:29.670
[ Door creaks ]

06:31.752 --> 06:34.394
‐You're supposed to be
at work in an hour.

06:34.394 --> 06:36.597
‐I know.

06:42.082 --> 06:44.284
‐You okay?

06:47.848 --> 06:49.650
Ohh.

06:53.654 --> 06:56.416
Maybe you should call in sick.

06:56.416 --> 06:59.499
‐I'll be fine.
It just...

06:59.499 --> 07:03.704
just hits me sometimes...
out of nowhere.

07:08.268 --> 07:10.150
Work's good.

07:12.152 --> 07:14.154
It's a distraction.

07:15.796 --> 07:17.998
‐That's new.
‐What?

07:20.641 --> 07:22.482
‐Homeless woman.

07:22.482 --> 07:24.565
I see her a lot
outside the restaurant.

07:24.565 --> 07:26.767
‐It's good.
‐It's okay.

07:29.169 --> 07:31.291
‐Well, maybe
it's just the working nights.

07:31.291 --> 07:33.694
You may need more sun.

07:33.694 --> 07:36.256
‐Nights are better.

07:36.256 --> 07:39.219
It's when it's the hardest.

07:39.219 --> 07:41.862
‐Some of you were alive
when Neil Armstrong

07:41.862 --> 07:43.584
first set foot on the moon.

07:43.584 --> 07:48.869
I wasn't, but I've watched
that footage at least 100 times.

07:48.869 --> 07:51.391
It still gives me goose bumps.

07:51.391 --> 07:54.394
That this nation ‐‐ we were able
to accomplish something

07:54.394 --> 07:56.517
so profound ‐‐

07:56.517 --> 08:00.521
that the human race is capable
of leaving our planet

08:00.521 --> 08:02.643
and setting foot
on a celestial object

08:02.643 --> 08:05.686
that thousands of generations
before us have ‐‐

08:05.686 --> 08:07.367
have stared at with wonder

08:07.367 --> 08:10.010
and never imagining it
was within reach.

08:10.010 --> 08:12.533
It's proof of what
we can achieve

08:12.533 --> 08:15.175
when we set our sights
on the impossible

08:15.175 --> 08:17.818
and say, "You know what?

08:17.818 --> 08:19.700
It is possible."

08:19.700 --> 08:22.262
You talk of educating
and feeding our youth.

08:22.262 --> 08:25.706
Yes, we have that duty.

08:25.706 --> 08:30.350
But we also have the duty
to inspire them, Senator.

08:30.350 --> 08:33.353
<i>What is the point of being</i>
<i>healthy and educated</i>

08:33.353 --> 08:36.677
<i>if not to strive</i>
<i>for a higher purpose?</i>

08:36.677 --> 08:41.361
<i>I feel this as strongly as an</i>
<i>astronaut as I did in the Army.</i>

08:41.361 --> 08:43.724
‐Screen off.
‐We can watch if you want.

08:43.724 --> 08:46.126
‐No, no.

08:46.126 --> 08:47.968
Let's go eat outside.

08:47.968 --> 08:50.250
[ Wind rushing ]

08:55.736 --> 08:58.058
[ Spoon clatters ]
Oh.

08:58.058 --> 09:00.220
[ Grunts ]

09:01.461 --> 09:03.103
[ Thumping lightly ]

09:07.107 --> 09:09.389
‐Everything okay down there?

09:09.389 --> 09:13.554
‐[ Snorting ]
‐[ Laughing ] Oh, my God.

09:13.554 --> 09:15.596
‐[ Snorts ]

09:15.596 --> 09:18.118
‐Did you really
sneak that out here?

09:18.118 --> 09:20.801
‐Captain "Hogerty"
is a sneaky fellow.

09:20.801 --> 09:23.083
‐Mm. Captain Hogerty
[Chuckling] it's been a while.

09:23.083 --> 09:25.726
‐It has been [snorts] a while.

09:25.726 --> 09:28.569
Your turn, Ms. Hogerty.

09:28.569 --> 09:31.932
‐[ Snorting ]

09:31.932 --> 09:33.213
‐And maybe you shouldn't do...

09:33.213 --> 09:35.776
[ Both laugh ]

09:43.824 --> 09:46.146
‐You know, I was thinking

09:46.146 --> 09:48.188
I'd like to start
painting again.

09:48.188 --> 09:50.751
‐That's a great idea.

09:50.751 --> 09:55.636
‐I've saved up a bit
for supplies ‐‐ oils, brushes.

09:55.636 --> 09:58.238
‐I can help you with supplies,
if you want.

10:00.440 --> 10:02.843
‐I was also thinking maybe
I could clean up

10:02.843 --> 10:06.647
Mom's shop downstairs,
turn it into a studio.

10:09.409 --> 10:10.771
My room's too small.

10:10.771 --> 10:12.292
I don't want to get paint
on the floor.

10:12.292 --> 10:13.534
And the fumes...

10:13.534 --> 10:15.215
‐I mean, if you want a place
to work,

10:15.215 --> 10:18.418
we can rent you a place.

10:18.418 --> 10:21.141
‐Well, that's a waste of money
when the shop's right here.

10:21.141 --> 10:22.783
‐Yeah, but it's so dirty
down there.

10:22.783 --> 10:24.785
It's so dusty.
‐I'll clean it, so...

10:24.785 --> 10:26.827
‐I mean ‐‐
No, it's like pests ‐‐

10:26.827 --> 10:28.829
cockroaches, rats ‐‐
‐Dad, I can clean it.

10:28.829 --> 10:30.631
You don't have to do anything.
It's fine.

10:30.631 --> 10:32.432
‐It's not about me
having to do anything.

10:32.432 --> 10:34.675
‐I want to work there.

10:37.277 --> 10:39.479
It means something to me.

10:51.732 --> 10:53.093
‐Finished?

10:54.254 --> 10:56.376
‐Yeah.

10:58.298 --> 11:01.582
‐[ Sighs ]

11:01.582 --> 11:05.506
I feel really useless sometimes.

11:05.506 --> 11:07.788
I don't know
the right thing to say.

11:07.788 --> 11:10.030
I don't know
the right thing to do.

11:13.033 --> 11:15.235
‐You're not useless.

11:17.838 --> 11:20.801
‐I can take you to work later,
if you want.

11:20.801 --> 11:23.524
[ Dog barking in distance ]

11:23.524 --> 11:26.206
[ Wind rushing ]

11:26.206 --> 11:29.249
[ Birds chirping ]

11:36.617 --> 11:38.058
‐If we go in the next
launch window ‐‐

11:38.058 --> 11:39.900
May of '33 ‐‐
it will only cost 22 more.

11:39.900 --> 11:42.783
‐So, then my question would be
whether that was $70 billion

11:42.783 --> 11:45.465
down the drain to begin with.

11:45.465 --> 11:49.029
‐We all know that the explosion
was not due to a design fault.

11:49.029 --> 11:50.551
It was human error, so, no,
I don't think anything ‐‐

11:50.551 --> 11:52.192
‐Well, you know,
in North Carolina,

11:52.192 --> 11:54.194
we could have used
some of that money for schools,

11:54.194 --> 11:57.437
for infrastructure,
job training, energy conversion.

11:57.437 --> 12:01.321
I'm talking hundreds of programs
to benefit thousands of people,

12:01.321 --> 12:05.886
not just the ‐‐ the jobs created
in my colleague's state.

12:05.886 --> 12:09.329
‐A mission to Mars will benefit
all of humankind.

12:09.329 --> 12:10.971
The technology we're developing,

12:10.971 --> 12:12.492
what we'll learn scientifically
is immeasurable...

12:12.492 --> 12:14.134
‐You know...
‐...not just for Mars, but ‐‐

12:14.134 --> 12:16.376
‐...what the Colonel said
about inspiration ‐‐

12:16.376 --> 12:17.898
It's all well and good.

12:17.898 --> 12:19.940
Now you go on about science
and technology.

12:19.940 --> 12:22.102
How does that help
the 5‐year‐old

12:22.102 --> 12:23.824
with no school lunch program?

12:23.824 --> 12:25.465
How does that help
the truck driver

12:25.465 --> 12:27.067
whose job has been automated
by a self‐driving ‐‐

12:27.067 --> 12:28.468
‐Senator, can I answer
your question?

12:28.468 --> 12:31.391
‐I'm not finished.
‐Uh, Madam Chairwoman,

12:31.391 --> 12:35.275
I believe that Ms. Ingram
should be given the opportunity.

12:35.275 --> 12:39.319
‐Let's hear her full answer.
‐Thank you.

12:39.319 --> 12:43.283
What we're confronting
is widespread drought,

12:43.283 --> 12:46.206
rising sea levels,
record extinction rates.

12:46.206 --> 12:47.608
There are currently

12:47.608 --> 12:50.771
over 900 million eco‐refugees
worldwide.

12:50.771 --> 12:53.694
In the States, cities like Miami
are disappearing.

12:53.694 --> 12:56.617
In my own home, New Orleans,
we've only survived

12:56.617 --> 12:58.699
because of massive levee
projects that are costing

12:58.699 --> 13:02.302
the taxpayers a lot more
than the Mars program.

13:02.302 --> 13:06.066
This is the world that
my children are facing,

13:06.066 --> 13:08.348
that all of our children
are facing.

13:08.348 --> 13:11.391
And as a parent, I would like
to secure their future

13:11.391 --> 13:13.674
and their children's future.

13:13.674 --> 13:16.917
If we don't start
to lay the foundations

13:16.917 --> 13:18.358
for interplanetary colonization
now ‐‐

13:18.358 --> 13:19.920
‐So, you're saying,
"To hell with it.

13:19.920 --> 13:21.522
Let's just go to Mars."

13:21.522 --> 13:23.323
‐Wrong.

13:23.323 --> 13:27.367
I'm saying let's tackle both ‐‐

13:27.367 --> 13:29.890
find solutions
here on Earth

13:29.890 --> 13:31.131
and an exploration ‐‐

13:31.131 --> 13:33.213
‐Well, I'm sorry, Ms. Ingram,

13:33.213 --> 13:35.095
but I'm not giving up on Earth.

13:35.095 --> 13:36.737
And when it comes
to our taxpayers,

13:36.737 --> 13:38.739
I'm investing in their home ‐‐

13:38.739 --> 13:43.504
this home ‐‐
not some other planet.

13:43.504 --> 13:47.387
‐We need at least a 10‐3 vote.

13:47.387 --> 13:50.110
If it's a squeaker,
folks will smell blood

13:50.110 --> 13:51.672
once it gets to the floor.

13:51.672 --> 13:55.115
‐We've got Chisolm, Lopez...
‐Barnes and Pasternak ‐‐

13:55.115 --> 13:58.438
I need six more confirmed yeses.

13:58.438 --> 14:00.921
‐Well, give me the names,
and I'll make the calls.

14:00.921 --> 14:04.204
‐I don't think
you're the right person.

14:04.204 --> 14:10.090
The response wasn't so hot
to your doomsday routine.

14:10.090 --> 14:11.932
‐That's not how I intended it
to come across.

14:11.932 --> 14:15.856
‐Well, I'm telling you
what they heard.

14:15.856 --> 14:18.418
Are those French fries
over there? Smells good.

14:18.418 --> 14:19.780
‐I can make some calls.

14:37.758 --> 14:49.770
♪♪

14:49.770 --> 14:57.217
♪♪

14:57.217 --> 15:00.220
[ Door unlocks ]

15:00.220 --> 15:01.622
♪♪

15:01.622 --> 15:02.703
[ Mid‐tempo music plays ]

15:02.703 --> 15:03.904
‐Vroom!

15:03.904 --> 15:06.146
Beep, beep, beep, beep, beep!

15:06.146 --> 15:08.829
‐I'm gonna catch you.
‐Fucking scooter.

15:08.829 --> 15:11.431
♪♪

15:11.431 --> 15:14.194
‐You opened up a Pandora's box,
you son of a bitch.

15:14.194 --> 15:17.598
‐Well, that's gonna be
your problem, not mine.

15:17.598 --> 15:19.399
Oh, here she comes.
‐Oh, is that so?

15:19.399 --> 15:21.602
[ Needle buzzes ]
‐Dangerous woman.

15:23.764 --> 15:25.085
[ Needle buzzes ]

15:37.538 --> 15:38.819
‐Well, in person would be better

15:38.819 --> 15:40.460
if you don't mind
a few house visits.

15:40.460 --> 15:43.784
‐Wherever you need me.
‐Castillo's testifying tomorrow.

15:43.784 --> 15:45.225
‐So he didn't settle.

15:45.225 --> 15:46.827
‐Said there wasn't
a number high enough.

15:46.827 --> 15:48.829
‐[ Sighs ]

15:48.829 --> 15:52.472
‐Well, let's see
who we can get you with, then.

15:52.472 --> 15:55.956
‐Giddy up.
It's pony show time.

15:55.956 --> 15:57.798
‐We'll see you in the morning.

16:03.764 --> 16:05.726
‐Senator.

16:06.887 --> 16:10.370
‐Good night.
‐Yeah.

16:10.370 --> 16:13.253
‐How bad is it?
Honestly?

16:13.253 --> 16:15.696
[ Door closes ]

16:15.696 --> 16:18.218
‐Buddy of mine's a trainer
at the Fair Grounds.

16:18.218 --> 16:22.903
He said to me once doping
a horse is never a sure bet,

16:22.903 --> 16:25.305
but the dope don't hurt.
[ Laughs ]

16:25.305 --> 16:29.069
‐I need the odds.

16:29.069 --> 16:31.752
‐It's a long shot.

16:31.752 --> 16:34.034
‐You got any voodoo
we don't know about,

16:34.034 --> 16:36.036
now's the time to use it.

16:36.036 --> 16:46.607
♪♪

16:46.607 --> 16:49.369
♪♪

16:49.369 --> 16:52.012
[ Vacuum humming ]

16:52.012 --> 16:54.374
♪♪

16:54.374 --> 16:56.857
‐Maybe it's his voice
they need to hear.

16:56.857 --> 17:01.101
♪♪

17:01.101 --> 17:03.423
Maybe he needs this
as much as you do.

17:03.423 --> 17:07.548
♪♪

17:07.548 --> 17:10.631
And I ain't saying two messes
make things clean.

17:10.631 --> 17:13.313
♪♪

17:13.313 --> 17:16.757
But his dirt ‐‐

17:16.757 --> 17:18.759
it's got something
different than yours.

17:18.759 --> 17:22.603
♪♪

17:22.603 --> 17:26.567
One of you is the star.

17:26.567 --> 17:28.769
The other is the dust.

17:30.370 --> 17:32.492
[ Cellphone ringing ]

17:32.492 --> 17:38.338
♪♪

17:38.338 --> 17:41.181
‐Answer.

17:41.181 --> 17:43.143
‐Hello, Tom.

17:45.065 --> 17:47.267
Are you clean‐shaven?

17:50.270 --> 17:53.954
‐Why?
‐Are you?

17:53.954 --> 17:56.677
‐Yes.
‐Good.

17:56.677 --> 17:58.879
I want you to come
to Washington.

18:00.921 --> 18:02.362
[ Up‐tempo music plays ]

18:02.362 --> 18:03.764
‐What was that?
‐It's just for the day.

18:03.764 --> 18:07.568
I'll be back tomorrow night.
‐Yeah, okay.

18:07.568 --> 18:09.489
‐Hey, you'll take Apollo
for a walk in the morning,

18:09.489 --> 18:11.331
fill up his bowl?

18:11.331 --> 18:12.853
‐Yeah, sure.

18:12.853 --> 18:14.695
‐You know,
I‐I don't have to do this.

18:14.695 --> 18:16.657
‐Yeah, I can't hear you, Dad.

18:16.657 --> 18:18.779
‐I said,
"I don't have to do this."

18:18.779 --> 18:20.541
‐I'll be fine.
‐All right.

18:20.541 --> 18:22.543
And you'll call me
if you need anything?

18:22.543 --> 18:24.184
‐What?
‐I said, "If you need

18:24.184 --> 18:25.385
anything, call me."

18:25.385 --> 18:28.509
‐Yes, yes. I will.
Travel safe.

18:28.509 --> 18:29.790
‐All right ‐‐
just want you to know,

18:29.790 --> 18:31.752
I started to
clear out downstairs.

18:31.752 --> 18:33.313
‐Dad, I really ‐‐
I can't hear you.

18:33.313 --> 18:35.716
‐I said I started to clear out

18:35.716 --> 18:37.197
down there in the tattoo par‐‐

18:37.197 --> 18:39.279
‐It's too loud.
I got to get back to work.

18:39.279 --> 18:42.122
‐Say again?
‐I have to go.

18:42.122 --> 18:44.845
Travel safe.

18:44.845 --> 18:46.527
[ Cellphone chimes ]

18:50.010 --> 18:52.212
‐[ Sighs ]

18:54.254 --> 19:02.262
♪♪

19:02.262 --> 19:03.664
‐Here you go, hon.

19:03.664 --> 19:06.266
Tomorrow?
‐Tomorrow.

19:06.266 --> 19:08.428
♪♪

19:08.428 --> 19:10.511
‐Can I stay at your place
tonight?

19:10.511 --> 19:12.633
My dad's out of town.

19:12.633 --> 19:15.435
I haven't had been by myself
in the house since...

19:15.435 --> 19:18.959
‐Yeah. Of course.

19:18.959 --> 19:20.160
‐Thanks.

19:23.964 --> 19:26.006
[ Panel chimes ]

19:26.006 --> 19:35.776
♪♪

19:35.776 --> 19:38.498
‐If Senator Mills comes at you,
just be brief.

19:38.498 --> 19:40.420
Do not engage with her.

19:40.420 --> 19:42.863
‐Yeah, and avoid
the climate change argument.

19:42.863 --> 19:45.105
That did not go down well.

19:45.105 --> 19:46.547
‐I've got our NASA engineers

19:46.547 --> 19:48.108
amending the report
from our end,

19:48.108 --> 19:51.592
so there's no need to go
into anything too technical.

19:51.592 --> 19:54.434
‐Just talk about your
experiences on the Moon,

19:54.434 --> 19:58.118
the forward momentum,
inspirations ‐‐

19:58.118 --> 20:01.241
‐You're saying
you want me to win them over.

20:01.241 --> 20:03.403
‐I am.
‐Got it.

20:03.403 --> 20:07.047
‐[ Chuckles ] Good.
Okay, I'm gonna turn in.

20:07.047 --> 20:09.970
I got a 6:00 a. m.
with the Chief‐of‐Staff.

20:09.970 --> 20:12.052
‐Is the President on board
with this?

20:14.054 --> 20:16.537
‐We're trying.

20:16.537 --> 20:19.059
‐Well, I should turn in, too.

20:19.059 --> 20:23.544
‐Um, there's one more talking
point, if you've got a second.

20:23.544 --> 20:25.385
‐Okay.

20:30.350 --> 20:32.112
‐Glad to have you here, Tom.
‐Good to see you, Bob.

20:32.112 --> 20:35.996
‐Yeah. Good night.
‐Night.

20:35.996 --> 20:40.240
[ Door opens, closes ]

20:40.240 --> 20:44.965
I know I'm asking a lot,
but this is big of you.

20:44.965 --> 20:47.167
I want to acknowledge that ‐‐
‐It's got nothing to do with me.

20:47.167 --> 20:49.570
‐Yes, it does.
It was your crew.

20:49.570 --> 20:51.932
[ Sighs ]

20:51.932 --> 20:54.294
Tom...

20:54.294 --> 20:57.377
when I relieved you
of your command,

20:57.377 --> 20:58.819
it's because I thought

20:58.819 --> 21:00.821
it was the best thing
to do at that time.

21:00.821 --> 21:05.506
‐This is a conversation that
I don't want to have with you.

21:05.506 --> 21:09.590
‐Okay.
I thought I would clear the air.

21:09.590 --> 21:12.753
‐I'm here for Mattie
and the crew.

21:12.753 --> 21:15.716
That's why I'm here.
It's Kayla's mission now.

21:15.716 --> 21:18.358
I gonna make sure she finishes
everything that we started.

21:18.358 --> 21:19.840
‐Good.
‐That's my duty to the mission.

21:19.840 --> 21:21.361
‐Mm‐hmm.

21:21.361 --> 21:25.846
‐My own focus right now
is my daughter.

21:25.846 --> 21:28.168
‐You're back in touch?
‐Yeah.

21:28.168 --> 21:29.890
She's staying with me
at the house.

21:29.890 --> 21:32.973
‐How is she?
‐It's getting late.

21:32.973 --> 21:34.695
Are we done?

21:36.897 --> 21:39.219
‐I was just asking.
‐I'll see you tomorrow.

21:39.219 --> 21:42.222
‐Here's your brief.

21:42.222 --> 21:45.746
‐Good night.

21:45.746 --> 21:49.069
[ Door opens, closes ]

21:54.835 --> 21:57.678
[ Birds chirping ]

22:37.838 --> 22:40.040
‐I don't want to
get mixed up in all this.

22:40.040 --> 22:41.762
You know,
it's not good for Charlotte.

22:41.762 --> 22:45.125
‐I'm hoping only the Senator's
gonna see it.

22:45.125 --> 22:47.968
‐Why does it have to be me?

22:47.968 --> 22:50.611
‐You're the commander's wife.

22:50.611 --> 22:53.373
If you write it,
everyone else signs on.

22:58.298 --> 23:00.701
‐[ Sighs ] Okay.

23:02.743 --> 23:04.184
‐I owe you one.

23:04.184 --> 23:05.666
‐No.

23:05.666 --> 23:08.428
Matt would have wanted me to.

23:08.428 --> 23:13.874
‐My greatest fear was that
he would be shot down

23:13.874 --> 23:17.437
and there would be
no body to bury.

23:17.437 --> 23:19.920
He survived the war,
but still...

23:19.920 --> 23:23.604
[Voice breaking]
there was no body to...

23:23.604 --> 23:25.766
‐Take as much time as you need.

23:37.297 --> 23:41.982
‐My son went fighting overseas
to defend his country.

23:41.982 --> 23:48.909
That I understood, even if ‐‐
as a parent ‐‐

23:48.909 --> 23:51.111
it wasn't what I wanted.

23:53.594 --> 23:58.238
But this ‐‐ there is no reason.

23:58.238 --> 24:01.121
Space? Why?
For what?

24:01.121 --> 24:05.085
This didn't need to happen.

24:05.085 --> 24:07.247
I ask this Committee

24:07.247 --> 24:09.690
to reconsider funding
for this project,

24:09.690 --> 24:11.251
so that more parents

24:11.251 --> 24:14.374
don't have to suffer the loss
that we have.

24:14.374 --> 24:20.300
♪♪

24:20.300 --> 24:22.342
‐Apollo!

24:22.342 --> 24:27.387
♪♪

24:27.387 --> 24:29.790
Apollo!

24:29.790 --> 24:31.952
‐We now invite
Captain Thomas Hagerty to speak

24:31.952 --> 24:33.514
before the Committee.

24:33.514 --> 24:42.282
♪♪

24:42.282 --> 24:51.091
♪♪

24:51.091 --> 24:54.535
Would you like to make
an opening statement?

24:54.535 --> 24:56.737
‐Madam Chairwoman,

24:56.737 --> 24:59.820
distinguished members
of the Committee,

24:59.820 --> 25:02.022
I don't have
a prepared statement.

25:04.545 --> 25:09.229
As a husband, speaking to the
spouses who lost their partners,

25:09.229 --> 25:12.272
I know what it means
to lose a loved one too early.

25:14.194 --> 25:16.356
As a father speaking
to the mothers and fathers

25:16.356 --> 25:18.078
who lost their children,

25:18.078 --> 25:22.162
I have a daughter,
and she means everything to me.

25:22.162 --> 25:24.685
♪♪

25:24.685 --> 25:27.327
And if I lost her, I don't know
if I could handle that.

25:27.327 --> 25:31.011
♪♪

25:31.011 --> 25:35.255
So out of respect
to Mr. and Mrs. Castillo

25:35.255 --> 25:38.699
and to all the families,

25:38.699 --> 25:41.622
I think it would be
inappropriate for me

25:41.622 --> 25:46.386
to assume to justify the deaths
of their loved ones.

25:48.388 --> 25:50.871
I would prefer
not to answer questions.

25:53.794 --> 25:56.997
And that completes my statement.
Thank you.

25:57.758 --> 25:59.399
[ Indistinct conversations ]

25:59.399 --> 26:03.403
‐Tom, I flew you here
to testify.

26:03.403 --> 26:05.686
‐It didn't feel right.

26:05.686 --> 26:08.048
‐So you say nothing?
You just hand out condolences ‐‐

26:08.048 --> 26:10.010
‐Let me do this my way.

26:12.853 --> 26:15.816
‐Mr. ‐‐ Mr. Castillo?

26:15.816 --> 26:17.057
Ma'am?

26:18.859 --> 26:21.061
May I speak to you for a moment?

26:24.665 --> 26:27.988
‐Hey. Yeah.

26:27.988 --> 26:29.229
Good boy.

26:29.229 --> 26:31.431
‐Nothing showed up for a week.

26:33.594 --> 26:37.798
Searched downriver all the way
to Venice and back ‐‐

26:37.798 --> 26:40.961
no body, though.

26:40.961 --> 26:45.806
We buried the casket empty,
just like you.

26:50.370 --> 26:56.697
I get it,
that feeling of helplessness.

26:56.697 --> 27:01.181
‐Yeah, I'm sorry
you lost your wife.

27:01.181 --> 27:03.984
But it's not the same.

27:03.984 --> 27:06.867
This was preventable.
‐[ Breathes deeply ]

27:08.148 --> 27:11.712
What we do is dangerous.
People are gonna die.

27:11.712 --> 27:13.834
‐That's what we're
trying to stop.

27:13.834 --> 27:16.717
‐You won't.

27:16.717 --> 27:21.041
Not as long as there are people
like your son ‐‐

27:21.041 --> 27:22.843
and, I suppose, myself.

27:22.843 --> 27:25.165
I would have given anything

27:25.165 --> 27:27.928
to have been on that rocket
with him.

27:30.130 --> 27:33.053
Let me ask you,
would he have been happy

27:33.053 --> 27:37.137
as a lawyer or anything else?

27:37.137 --> 27:40.460
‐He'd be alive.

27:40.460 --> 27:43.864
‐Would he have been happy?

27:43.864 --> 27:47.227
‐He hated me for criticizing ‐‐
‐That's not true.

27:47.227 --> 27:49.830
‐He did.
‐No.

27:49.830 --> 27:54.555
‐Thanksgiving.
‐He was drunk.

27:54.555 --> 27:56.517
‐He told me he was sick of me...
‐He didn't mean it.

27:56.517 --> 27:58.358
‐...for making him feel small.

27:58.358 --> 28:00.360
‐He did not mean it.

28:00.360 --> 28:02.442
‐Well, you saw his eyes.

28:02.442 --> 28:05.285
‐[ Sighs ]

28:05.285 --> 28:07.728
‐Did he ever tell you
how much he hated me?

28:07.728 --> 28:09.730
‐No, sir.

28:09.730 --> 28:11.772
‐What did he say about us?

28:11.772 --> 28:16.016
‐He never spoke to me
about his family.

28:16.016 --> 28:17.698
‐You see?

28:21.742 --> 28:27.948
‐Your son loved what he did ‐‐
that I know.

28:35.075 --> 28:36.757
Here.

28:36.757 --> 28:39.119
I'm gonna show you.

28:45.766 --> 28:50.490
Video.
P‐Foxtrot Four.

28:50.490 --> 28:52.452
Back to start.

28:54.895 --> 28:56.777
You, too.

28:56.777 --> 29:03.744
♪♪

29:03.744 --> 29:05.866
Sync video.
[ Beeps ]

29:05.866 --> 29:08.629
‐Sync video.
[ Beeps ]

29:08.629 --> 29:11.391
‐Play.

29:11.391 --> 29:13.233
The aurora.

29:13.233 --> 29:15.876
♪♪

29:15.876 --> 29:18.078
At that altitude,
you can touch it.

29:18.078 --> 29:21.401
♪♪

29:21.401 --> 29:24.084
Every color ‐‐

29:24.084 --> 29:28.408
colors
you've never seen before ‐‐

29:28.408 --> 29:32.052
and lights moving
all around you.

29:32.052 --> 29:34.414
♪♪

29:34.414 --> 29:37.337
The universe.

29:37.337 --> 29:38.939
And it's right there.

29:38.939 --> 29:49.870
♪♪

29:49.870 --> 29:54.474
And I always think
of Sagan's words ‐‐

29:54.474 --> 29:57.237
"Everyone you ever heard of,

29:57.237 --> 30:01.081
every human being that ever was,

30:01.081 --> 30:03.884
lived out their lives...

30:03.884 --> 30:05.485
on a mote of dust,

30:05.485 --> 30:08.649
suspended in a sun beam."

30:08.649 --> 30:12.693
And your boy rode that beam.

30:12.693 --> 30:21.702
♪♪

30:21.702 --> 30:28.669
♪♪

30:28.669 --> 30:33.273
And the two of you
gave him a life

30:33.273 --> 30:35.996
that let him live that dream.

30:35.996 --> 30:43.003
♪♪

30:53.694 --> 30:55.976
‐I don't see
the Castillos' name on this.

30:55.976 --> 30:58.138
‐Senator, the Castillos
are reconsidering

30:58.138 --> 31:00.541
their position on the lawsuit.

31:00.541 --> 31:04.104
I spoke to them.

31:04.104 --> 31:05.706
‐Look, the letter is moving.

31:05.706 --> 31:08.268
But I have to think
about the bigger picture.

31:08.268 --> 31:09.710
I'm considered
about eleven‐five.

31:09.710 --> 31:11.471
I mean, you cut corners,

31:11.471 --> 31:13.754
where are we
a year and a half from now?

31:13.754 --> 31:15.435
You're showing me
another one of these letters.

31:15.435 --> 31:18.198
‐The transit vehicle
can survive for two years.

31:18.198 --> 31:21.081
Everything pre‐placed on Mars
is fully operational ‐‐

31:21.081 --> 31:22.803
no new builds.

31:22.803 --> 31:25.606
We can do this safely
at half the cost.

31:25.606 --> 31:27.487
Eitan's been through it
line by line.

31:27.487 --> 31:30.130
‐I'm confident we can make
this number work.

31:34.254 --> 31:36.176
‐Well, it has been a long day,

31:36.176 --> 31:37.538
so I have to process
all of this.

31:37.538 --> 31:39.059
‐Does that mean we have a maybe?

31:39.059 --> 31:40.460
‐That's means
I got to get home to my kids.

31:40.460 --> 31:42.983
‐I'll walk you out.

31:42.983 --> 31:44.625
She wants to make a deal.

31:44.625 --> 31:46.907
She never would have taken
the meeting if she didn't.

31:46.907 --> 31:48.709
‐Can you hang around
a couple of more days?

31:48.709 --> 31:51.431
‐However long it takes.
‐How about you two?

31:51.431 --> 31:52.913
‐Well, I‐I thought we were
heading back tonight.

31:52.913 --> 31:56.517
I got the crew doing
sim training tomorrow.

31:56.517 --> 31:57.958
‐Tom?

31:57.958 --> 31:59.760
‐I have to talk to my daughter.

31:59.760 --> 32:01.842
‐Well, you know, I‐I can cancel
if you need me to stay.

32:01.842 --> 32:03.443
‐No, you should
stay on schedule.

32:03.443 --> 32:05.445
Jason. Jason.

32:05.445 --> 32:07.007
[ Indistinct conversations ]

32:07.007 --> 32:09.449
Could you get the jet ready?
At Reagan?

32:09.449 --> 32:10.851
[ Piano music plays ]

32:10.851 --> 32:19.299
♪♪

32:19.299 --> 32:20.340
[ Music stops ]

32:20.340 --> 32:23.143
‐Are we leaving?
‐You are.

32:23.143 --> 32:24.464
[ Piano chord plays ]

32:24.464 --> 32:25.866
I need to stay.

32:25.866 --> 32:27.628
‐You're not coming back with us?

32:27.628 --> 32:30.631
‐I can't.
‐I want to stay here with you.

32:39.319 --> 32:40.841
‐I was just calling her.

32:40.841 --> 32:43.884
Uh, she didn't answer.

32:43.884 --> 32:47.487
‐Tom, we really need you here.

32:47.487 --> 32:49.009
‐Uh, it's just
the first time that

32:49.009 --> 32:52.773
she's been in the house alone
without me.

32:52.773 --> 32:55.656
‐Okay, so do you want me
to send someone to check on her?

32:55.656 --> 32:57.337
‐No.

32:57.337 --> 32:59.860
‐I could hold the plane
for a while

32:59.860 --> 33:01.181
if you want to try her back.

33:01.181 --> 33:02.783
‐No.

33:04.585 --> 33:06.066
‐Let me send someone.

33:06.066 --> 33:07.588
‐I don't want her to feel
that she's being ‐‐

33:07.588 --> 33:11.712
<i>‐New message. Denise.</i>
‐Oh.

33:11.712 --> 33:13.754
Play.

33:13.754 --> 33:15.636
<i>‐Hey.</i>
<i>Can't call you back right now.</i>

33:15.636 --> 33:17.678
<i>It's a hectic night here,</i>
<i>but no worries</i>

33:17.678 --> 33:20.601
<i>if you need to stay</i>
<i>in D. C. ‐‐ I'll be fine.</i>

33:20.601 --> 33:24.805
<i>Also, I wanted to say thank you</i>
<i>for what you did downstairs.</i>

33:24.805 --> 33:26.567
<i>It means a lot to me.</i>

33:26.567 --> 33:28.809
<i>Okay, good luck.</i>
<i>See you when I see you.</i>

33:28.809 --> 33:31.532
<i>Love you.</i>
[ Cellphone chimes ]

33:31.532 --> 33:33.774
‐I'm sticking around.

33:33.774 --> 33:44.545
♪♪

33:44.545 --> 33:56.236
♪♪

33:56.236 --> 34:07.287
♪♪

34:07.287 --> 34:11.091
♪♪

34:11.091 --> 34:13.974
‐Madam President.
‐Laz.

34:13.974 --> 34:17.257
‐Madam President.

34:17.257 --> 34:21.141
‐I must say, it's quite an honor
to meet you, Captain.

34:25.065 --> 34:28.148
‐If you truly honored
what we do,

34:28.148 --> 34:30.511
you'd call Senator Mills,

34:30.511 --> 34:34.314
tip her off the fence.

34:34.314 --> 34:37.477
Doing nothing honors nothing,

34:37.477 --> 34:41.001
and that would be disgraceful
towards those who died.

34:46.406 --> 34:49.129
‐[ Chuckles ]

34:49.129 --> 34:52.252
Clarksville, Missouri.
That's where you're from.

34:52.252 --> 34:54.094
‐Yes, ma'am.

34:54.094 --> 34:59.299
‐We Midwesterners
don't mince words, do we?

34:59.299 --> 35:01.301
‐Doers, not talkers.

35:01.301 --> 35:04.104
‐I've been to Clarksville ‐‐

35:04.104 --> 35:07.347
pretty poor stretch
of the river.

35:07.347 --> 35:09.830
‐I'm proud of my hometown.

35:09.830 --> 35:11.712
My mother was a lock operator.

35:11.712 --> 35:15.395
That's why I was raised there.

35:15.395 --> 35:17.197
‐What I'm trying to do

35:17.197 --> 35:19.720
is make places
like your hometown

35:19.720 --> 35:21.481
a little better off.

35:21.481 --> 35:24.244
There's only so much money
to go around.

35:24.244 --> 35:29.770
Spending it unwisely ‐‐
that's disgraceful.

35:29.770 --> 35:32.452
‐You lost Missouri,

35:32.452 --> 35:36.056
and you're not
gonna win it next year,

35:36.056 --> 35:38.979
so forgive me if I have
a difficult time

35:38.979 --> 35:41.301
pretending that you're gonna be
sending the money that way.

35:41.301 --> 35:43.063
I think that you're resistant

35:43.063 --> 35:45.906
because this is a project
of the previous administration.

35:45.906 --> 35:47.508
‐Hmm.

35:47.508 --> 35:50.991
Did you speak to my predecessor
like this?

35:50.991 --> 35:54.314
‐I didn't have to.
We went to the Moon.

35:54.314 --> 35:55.716
We brought back more of it

35:55.716 --> 35:57.998
than all the Apollo missions
combined.

35:57.998 --> 35:59.279
We did it for the country.

35:59.279 --> 36:01.922
We did for science.

36:01.922 --> 36:05.886
And I was able to bring him
back one of these

36:05.886 --> 36:08.088
from the Kepler Crater.

36:14.454 --> 36:16.857
‐Is this a bribe?

36:16.857 --> 36:19.299
‐No, ma'am, it's a challenge.

36:19.299 --> 36:22.422
Get us past the Moon.

36:22.422 --> 36:24.985
Own it.

36:24.985 --> 36:28.869
‐We're not asking for public
support, just the call to Mills.

36:28.869 --> 36:31.552
You can distance yourself
politically for now,

36:31.552 --> 36:35.475
and then, when we succeed,
it's all yours.

36:35.475 --> 36:46.647
♪♪

36:46.647 --> 36:58.619
♪♪

36:58.619 --> 37:07.908
♪♪

37:07.908 --> 37:10.631
[ Coins clinking ]

37:10.631 --> 37:13.954
[ Jukebox playing ]

37:13.954 --> 37:17.878
‐[ Sighs ] It's gorgeous.

37:17.878 --> 37:21.281
‐I want it right here.

37:21.281 --> 37:25.405
‐Uh, your Dad would divorce me.
‐It's fine.

37:25.405 --> 37:27.327
He can move to Houston,

37:27.327 --> 37:29.369
and then we can have the place
to ourselves.

37:29.369 --> 37:30.571
‐[ Chuckles ]

37:30.571 --> 37:32.092
♪♪

37:32.092 --> 37:35.856
Right there.

37:35.856 --> 37:39.379
‐You're so much more talented
than I am.

37:39.379 --> 37:43.864
♪♪

37:43.864 --> 37:46.827
<i>‐We had a perfect record ‐‐</i>
<i>not a single incident.</i>

37:46.827 --> 37:49.189
<i>‐All it takes is one ‐‐</i>
<i>five people lose their lives.</i>

37:49.189 --> 37:51.311
<i>‐All it takes for what?</i>

37:51.311 --> 37:54.274
<i>For human error</i>
<i>in a single incident</i>

37:54.274 --> 37:57.598
<i>to frighten a country away</i>
<i>from its aspirations,</i>

37:57.598 --> 38:00.120
<i>the very ideals that built it</i>
<i>in the first place?</i>

38:00.120 --> 38:01.762
<i>No. We ‐‐</i>
<i>We can't lose our courage.</i>

38:01.762 --> 38:03.443
<i>And when I'm talking</i>
<i>about courage,</i>

38:03.443 --> 38:05.045
<i>I'm not talking about</i>
<i>the courage it takes</i>

38:05.045 --> 38:07.528
<i>for someone to step</i>
<i>on the Moon or on Mars.</i>

38:07.528 --> 38:10.891
<i>I'm talking about the courage</i>
<i>of all of us to be</i>

38:10.891 --> 38:13.574
<i>the best version of ourselves.</i>

38:13.574 --> 38:15.856
<i>The honor of being</i>
<i>an astronaut comes</i>

38:15.856 --> 38:18.659
<i>because, despite your training,</i>

38:18.659 --> 38:20.701
<i>despite the thousands of people</i>

38:20.701 --> 38:23.143
<i>that work so hard</i>
<i>to keep you safe,</i>

38:23.143 --> 38:24.865
<i>there's always the chance</i>

38:24.865 --> 38:26.907
<i>that you'll make</i>
<i>the ultimate sacrifice,</i>

38:26.907 --> 38:29.550
<i>and that's only palatable</i>
<i>if you know</i>

38:29.550 --> 38:35.796
<i>that the country will support,</i>
<i>continuing to carry that torch.</i>

38:35.796 --> 38:38.078
<i>‐Ellen Dawes ‐‐ the wife</i>
<i>of Commander Dawes ‐‐</i>

38:38.078 --> 38:39.720
<i>she wrote a letter.</i>

38:39.720 --> 38:42.482
<i>She said that ending</i>
<i>the Mars program would,</i>

38:42.482 --> 38:44.444
<i>quote,</i>
<i>"Dishonor her husband's death."</i>

38:44.444 --> 38:47.808
<i>Strong words.</i>
<i>‐Honest words.</i>

38:47.808 --> 38:49.089
<i>And I agree with her.</i>

38:49.089 --> 38:50.571
[ Indistinct conversations ]

38:50.571 --> 38:52.372
‐You can vote no if you need
to save face,

38:52.372 --> 38:55.696
but I need you to get Spritzer
and Langford off the fence.

38:55.696 --> 38:59.700
[ Conversations continue ]

38:59.700 --> 39:02.743
Come on.
You fought the good fight, Ed.

39:05.105 --> 39:06.547
[ Glass thumps lightly ]

39:06.547 --> 39:10.430
‐Installments.
No lump sum.

39:10.430 --> 39:12.553
‐Fair enough.

39:14.555 --> 39:16.557
‐There's an aluminum factory
in Durham ‐‐

39:16.557 --> 39:18.759
‐Oh!
Now we're getting somewhere.

39:18.759 --> 39:22.563
Hey, another, uh, vodka soda
for my friend,

39:22.563 --> 39:24.244
and I'll have another bourbon.

39:25.766 --> 39:29.249
‐Anything else, sir,
before we land?

39:29.249 --> 39:31.051
‐Oh, I'm good.
Thank you.

39:31.051 --> 39:33.053
‐Ma'am?

39:33.053 --> 39:36.016
‐Oh, um, some Advil
if you have it.

39:36.016 --> 39:39.099
‐Let me check.

39:39.099 --> 39:41.021
‐Out cold.

39:41.021 --> 39:44.144
‐Yeah, I wish I could
sleep like that.

39:44.144 --> 39:47.508
‐Flaring up?
‐It always gets bad on planes.

39:47.508 --> 39:49.790
I didn't take any meds
this morning.

39:54.234 --> 40:00.200
My mother always told me
that I said "thank you"

40:00.200 --> 40:04.765
and "sorry" too much,
so...

40:04.765 --> 40:08.088
I stopped saying either.

40:08.088 --> 40:09.970
But I owe you both.

40:09.970 --> 40:13.213
‐Not necessary.
Team effort.

40:13.213 --> 40:14.975
‐You took us over the top.

40:14.975 --> 40:17.818
‐Well, I wouldn't count
your chickens.

40:17.818 --> 40:19.459
‐[ Chuckles ]

40:19.459 --> 40:22.543
Well, 48 hours ago,
I didn't have any chickens,

40:22.543 --> 40:24.745
and now I can hear
some clucking.

40:32.673 --> 40:34.835
Would you consider coming back?

40:40.120 --> 40:42.963
I‐I know that
Denise is your first priority,

40:42.963 --> 40:44.204
but since
you said that she's doing ‐‐

40:44.204 --> 40:46.486
‐Coming back how?
Training?

40:46.486 --> 40:48.569
‐As commander.

40:53.574 --> 40:56.096
‐Could I get a cup
of coffee, please?

40:56.096 --> 40:58.378
‐I mean, obviously,
I'd have to talk to Bob and ‐‐

40:58.378 --> 41:00.541
and get NASA approval and ‐‐

41:00.541 --> 41:02.543
‐Where's this coming from?

41:02.543 --> 41:04.665
‐Um.

41:04.665 --> 41:06.787
[ Chuckling ] I've put a lot
of thought into it.

41:06.787 --> 41:10.310
‐Well, it seems pretty sudden.

41:10.310 --> 41:12.753
‐I didn't ever want you
to leave.

41:12.753 --> 41:16.316
It was a mistake to let you go.

41:16.316 --> 41:19.159
Kayla could be your second.
‐It's her crew.

41:19.159 --> 41:22.843
‐We've got one shot at this...

41:22.843 --> 41:25.646
and I need the best team.

41:27.007 --> 41:28.609
‐Is that the reason,

41:28.609 --> 41:32.252
or is it because I can help you
get the money?

41:32.252 --> 41:33.894
‐That's a big part of it.

41:39.179 --> 41:41.301
‐We'd have to cut someone.

41:41.301 --> 41:43.584
‐So we cut someone.

41:43.584 --> 41:46.987
None of the rest are anywhere
near as qualified.

41:49.149 --> 41:52.993
‐[ Sighs ]

41:54.795 --> 41:58.198
‐Denise is doing well...now.

41:58.198 --> 41:59.560
I don't know how she'll be
in a year.

41:59.560 --> 42:01.842
I don't know
how she'll be tomorrow.

42:01.842 --> 42:04.645
‐I understand.
I'm willing to take that risk.

42:04.645 --> 42:06.967
‐Well, I don't know if I am.

42:12.212 --> 42:13.814
[ P. A. chimes ]
<i>‐All right, everyone.</i>

42:13.814 --> 42:15.576
<i>We're about to make</i>
<i>our final descent.</i>

42:15.576 --> 42:17.938
<i>We should be on the ground</i>
<i>in about 10 minutes.</i>

42:17.938 --> 42:20.140
‐Mandy. Seat belt.

42:22.142 --> 42:24.024
[ Seat belts click ]

42:25.465 --> 42:27.427
Ohh.
I hate landings.

42:27.427 --> 42:30.030
[ Engine roaring ]

42:30.030 --> 42:32.232
‐It's just the flaps.

43:02.262 --> 43:06.266
‐If you're still enough for long
enough, the lights will go off.

43:08.709 --> 43:13.113
Mom and me
used to play that game.

43:13.113 --> 43:14.795
‐I thought you were at work.

43:14.795 --> 43:17.077
‐Called in sick.

43:23.644 --> 43:26.807
‐You sick?
‐No.

43:33.774 --> 43:35.656
‐[ Chuckles ]

43:38.779 --> 43:41.702
It looks great.

43:41.702 --> 43:44.184
‐It's a start.

43:53.433 --> 43:55.556
Really still ‐‐

43:55.556 --> 43:58.999
In about a minute,
they'll go off.

43:58.999 --> 44:01.201
You have to barely breathe.

44:09.329 --> 44:11.972
‐They want me back.

44:13.934 --> 44:16.136
They want me to command.

44:22.462 --> 44:27.387
NASA might nix it.
I don't even know if I want to.

44:27.387 --> 44:31.832
You're the most
important thing, and...

44:31.832 --> 44:35.115
tell me to say no,
I'm gonna say no.

44:46.366 --> 44:48.408
But if I did do it...

44:52.012 --> 44:54.134
...do you think
we could make that work?

44:56.697 --> 45:00.941
I mean, you're so much better

45:00.941 --> 45:05.746
than I've seen you in so long.

45:05.746 --> 45:08.468
I think we can make it work.

45:08.468 --> 45:10.631
I think we could.

45:21.161 --> 45:24.925
Would you say something, please?

45:24.925 --> 45:28.529
‐Shh.

